<ns4894:section xmlns:ns4894="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.basicLanguage.commandLineArguments.commandLineArguments">
  <ns4895:title xmlns:ns4895="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Command Line Arguments</ns4895:title>
  <ns4896:para xmlns:ns4896="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">It is often useful to be able to supply further information when launching an
    application. This is done via command line arguments which can be supplied when launching
    the application from command line or an environment which allows you to specify command line arguments.
  </ns4896:para>
  <ns4897:para xmlns:ns4897="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The command line arguments are passed on to your <ns4898:literal xmlns:ns4898="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">main()</ns4898:literal> function of your application 
    as an array of strings:
    <ns4899:programlisting xmlns:ns4899="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
public static void main(String[] commandLineArgs) {...}
    </ns4899:programlisting>
  </ns4897:para>  
  <ns4900:para xmlns:ns4900="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Consider the following application which converts 2-dimensional cartesian coordinates to polar
    coordinates. The x and y coordinates are supplied as command line arguments:
    <ns4901:programlisting xmlns:ns4901="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" parse="text" href="src/ToPolar.java"/></ns4901:programlisting>
  </ns4900:para>  
  <ns4902:para xmlns:ns4902="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
     Running the application via
    <ns4903:programlisting xmlns:ns4903="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
 java ToPolar 1 1
   </ns4903:programlisting>
   yields the following output
   <ns4904:programlisting xmlns:ns4904="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
r = 1.4142135623730951
theta = 45.00000000000001
   </ns4904:programlisting>.
  </ns4902:para>
</ns4894:section>